segments.text: that he gave you, as you look back on it now, do you think that was appropriate advice?
It was wonderful advice.
I went up and went to work for the highway department back up
close to home in Atlanta.

The district office was located in Atlanta and I worked for them from January through May of the next year and transferred to the Bryan district because they knew I was going back to graduate school and it was a matter of convenience.
Two district engineers getting together said let's move Walton to Bryan so you can go to graduate school and they paid for it.
And then I worked for three months here in Bryan getting ready to go to graduate school.
And Saul Wright told me I needed an attitude adjustment, and so I went and got that two-year attitude adjustment and changed direction a little bit.
I was really going to come back in materials in the soils area.
I had some profs in undergraduate school that had really, I thought, turned me on to what I wanted to do.
I wanted in the general area of transportation, but I thought I'd specialize in soil.
But I went to the highway department.
I really came back in more pure transportation rather than materials.
But in my time up at the highway department, I was very well prepared.
I turned down a job offer with Exxon.
Well, big money.
I think I went to work for the highway department at $585 a month, and Exxon had offered me $700 a month.
Texaco had offered me $700 a month.
And so I was afraid, quite honestly, that had I taken either of those jobs with the two oil companies, I would have never come back.
And I felt like going to work for the highway department, I would, in fact, come back, and I did.
And to answer the question, was I prepared?
There's no question I was prepared.
Is there anything, looking back now with the clarity of hindsight, is there anything that you think A&M should have done more of or could have done better?
Haskell, you know, yeah, when I consider my whole career and the fact that not only was I an undergraduate student here, but I went through a master's and a Ph.D. program here.
Well, I've seen that, but primarily the undergraduate.
Yeah, but when I look at my career as a master's and a Ph.D. student and as a professor and a dean here and the things we did in those time periods, and I look back as an undergraduate student,
I can ask the question, why did so many students not make it in those days?
And so could the university have done something more in those days?
Perhaps so.
Perhaps they could have done a better job of retention of the student.
But were we admitting?
That's a good question.
No, no, there were a lot of them like old Ned, you know, coming from small high schools and preparation probably was not that good.
And
I don't know if the expectations were that high either, but I know the retention rate was not that good in those days, and a lot of students did not make it.
So that's about the only thing I could say, Haskell, as far as having good quality in the classroom and good profs and what have you.
I don't look back on my undergraduate days at all and say, boy, I had a bunch of lousy profs.
Those guys were great.
I will never forget.
To which ones would you give the highest marks?
I'm going to ask you the negative.
Who are the ones that you now think did the best job?
By name?
Yeah.
Oh, goodness.
There are 10 or 12 profs that were just absolutely magnificent to me in my undergraduate days.
And if I limit it to my pure civil engineering program, it has to be Neil Rowan, Wayne Dunlap,
Ted Hirsch, Howard Furr, all four rather demanding but just exceptional teachers, exceptional teachers.
There were a large number of other profs that I thoroughly enjoyed over in the supporting departments and what have you.
But I'd have to say it was really in my department.
I really didn't get turned on until I got to my department, quite honestly.
And so those are the folks that I just felt like did an absolutely stupendous job in helping me and getting me prepared and knowing what was right.
And they went to bat for me for graduate school.
They were ready to see me in graduate school.
Yeah, Walt and Ken as a graduate student at Texas A&M.
So those are the guys that really made a particular
impact on me as an undergraduate student.
Other than the sheer academics, what else did you learn at Texas A&M?
I really believe I learned teamwork.

I really believe I learned how to live with other people and get along with other people and give and take and share and compromise and do those things that you have to do to live in a civilian society.
I really believe I learned those things.
I learned a good work ethic.
There's no question that

By the time you got through an A&M preparation in engineering, and I can't speak for the other departments, but I think it's probably about the same, but I really know that by the time I got out, there was a work ethic there, that you worked for what you got, and that if you did your work well, there was a reward there for you.
And those things have not left me.
I learned that at A&M, how to do teamwork, how to work together.
If you were a consultant today to Texas A&M, whether it be A&M in general and or engineering, what advice would you give them about today and the future for Texas A&M?
I would try to give them some help on how do we identify that youngster that we want and that belongs here.
I hurt more on one thing than anything else in my total A&M experience, and that is knowing that today there are literally thousands of kids out there that want A&M so bad and they can't have it.
And there's not a solution to that, Haskell, as far as I know.
And I don't care what position I held out there.
I couldn't solve that problem and say, okay, if you want to, you can have it.
It's just not that way anymore.
But I would try to give some help to them in identifying those students that will make it so that we have extremely high retention, give those kids the opportunity.
I know when I went to the dean's office, we did some...

tracking of high schools all across the state and we looked at SATs and high school grades and high school rank and extracurricular activities and all these sort of things and said okay what kids are successful to us and you know we'd see those kids with fourteen hundred fifteen hundred SAT scores bust out and not make it and you'd say well why and we'd try to go back and look and see why and then we'd see this this high school kid that uh...
not necessarily a high SAT score, that was doing extremely well in our program.
Why?
And we tried to answer those questions.
I think that I, and maybe there exists this already, I don't know.
I'd put together a blue ribbon committee and say, people, let's look what it is out there that is the pool of
Let's look at what we're really trying to do as a state institution, land grant institution, and all the other space grants and sea grants and everything else that we have.
We do want to be the research institution as well as the academic institution.
What is it out there for us that we really want to bring into our institution
I don't know why it's not still a hit and miss to some extent.
I may be wrong, but I think maybe it is still a hit and miss to some extent.
I would try to really focus in on a real blue ribbon panel that could address those issues and try to do a better job of doing that.
And quite honestly, Haskell, if we did that, I think diversity would take care of itself.
I made a presentation a good number of years ago right after the
Oh, the decision that... Hopwood.
The Hopwood decision.
I had an opportunity to speak to one of the honor societies at the university.
And one of the questions that came to me after the presentation and question and answer period was, Dr. Walton, what do you think is, what do you think the impact of this decision is going to be?
I said it only means it's a difference of how we identify students.
It should be no more than that.
We've just got to do a different job of identifying those students that we really need to bring to this campus.
And the way we've been doing it, someone says it's the wrong way, so let's find a new way to do it.
And Jim Yow, I don't know if you remember Jim Yow.
Jim was head of the Civil Engineering Department at that time.
We had a discussion afterwards.
He kind of agreed with my basic premise there that, yes, we still can be diverse.
We can still bring in the students that we want to bring in.
We've just got to do a little bit different job of how we identify them and how we structure it.
And again, I'm not too sure we've done that yet.
What have we left out of your undergraduate days?
I think we pretty well covered the undergraduate today.
All right, then the last question is, what feelings do you carry in your heart today for Texas A&M?
You know, they're very strong.
hard to define.
You want to give something back.
You want to
You still want to spend your last days as an Aggie, you know?
You want to go to your grave as an Aggie, having never changed, no allegiance, nothing changes.
You want your last days still to be an Aggie, and you want to share it, you know, with everyone that you can.
There's just that part of belonging that...
You've got to be one to know that you are one.
I really believe that.
You've got to be an Aggie to know what an Aggie is.
I have very strong religious convictions in high school.
I have very strong convictions about my family and dedication to my family.
My dad taught me to, son, don't ever put anything before God.
Your family comes after that, but then don't put anything in front of your family past that.
And, man, I can pull A&M real close behind that.
You know, it's church and family.
Those Aggies come in a very strong third, you know.
It's just wonderful to be an Aggie.
Man, I wouldn't change anything.
And I go back and I look.
I have 15 very close relatives that are all A&M graduates and a daughter-in-law.

that's an Aggie, makes number 16, and my wife has nine Aggies on her side, so we put my 16 and her nine together, that's 25 Aggies that are pretty much in the immediate family, and so we've got maroon blood, and so we're not gonna be in danger of any of us losing sight of what it means to be an Aggie,
We all share those strong convictions about what it is.
When I left here as an undergraduate, knowing I was coming back to graduate school, I could hardly wait to get back, quite honestly.
It was hard for me to consider jobs outside of the A&M system.
When I thought about getting a Ph.D. degree, Fred Bunsen had arranged for me to go two or three different places.
I could have gone to Purdue.
I could have gone to the University of Texas.
I could have gone to Kansas State, his alma mater.
And he said, why leave the best?
And he says, when you get on the faculty here, he said, you're standing side by side to another applicant that's moving up the chain to tenure.
He said, you just got to be a little bit better than that graduate from somewhere else.
But he said, you'll get a shot at it.
And he said, I'm going to tell you what.
He said, the Aggie can be better every time.
And I got a lot of encouragement from Fred Benson to do that.
And so I've just got extremely deep feelings for A&M, not only from my undergraduate days,
you've got to understand that it was more than undergraduate days for me and my relationship with A&M.
It's just never-ending.
That's great.
I did skip one question, so this is a note to the typist.
Move this one back before that last question.
If you had the capacity to make a major gift to Texas A&M, somebody walks up to you and gives you a check for a million dollars and you've got to pass it on, if you
could make a major contribution to Texas A&M, for what purpose would you want that gift used?
What would be your favorite?
Haskell, I am definite on what I would do right now.
My brother and I established an endowed scholarship here.
That's behind us.
It would definitely go to the Texas A&M Press.
You're talking about the press as it's now named?
Yes.
Really?
There's no question.
I'm in love with the press.
How marvelous.
I have enjoyed so much.
I own a copy of every book that the press has ever published.
There aren't many of us who do.
I believe that reading is very fundamental.
My little grandson is a very
a very fine reader.
I have just, and his mother's a teacher, is the reason that they encouraged it so much.
But they did such a wonderful job.
And I just, it would go to the Texas A&M Press.
It would.
